== With inversion, it still splits

Even when something else comes first, the verb still splits in the same way.

- `Morgen sta ik vroeg op.`
- `In Amsterdam komt zij om negen uur aan.`
- `Vandaag neemt hij zijn laptop mee.`

So the word order changes, but the separated part still stays near the end.

== With modal verbs, the whole verb stays together

After modal verbs such as `willen`, `kunnen`, and `moeten`, the second verb goes to the end as an infinitive. In that position, the separable verb stays together.

- `Ik wil morgen vroeg opstaan.`
- `Wij kunnen om acht uur aankomen.`
- `Hij moet zijn jas meenemen.`
- `Zij wil haar vriendin opbellen.`

This is one of the biggest patterns to notice:

- main clause without modal -> `Ik sta op.`
- with modal -> `Ik wil opstaan.`

== In the perfect tense

In the perfect tense, many separable verbs use `ge-` between the first part and the main verb part.

- `opstaan` -> `opgestaan`
- `aankomen` -> `aangekomen`
- `meenemen` -> `meegenomen`
- `opbellen` -> `opgebeld`

